00:03:57.600 --> 00:03:59.395
Final Fantasy 13,
Metal Gear Solid

00:03:59.395 --> 00:04:03.260
4, both games kind of derided
for, in certain circles,

00:04:03.260 --> 00:04:05.310
the linearness of their games.

00:04:05.310 --> 00:04:07.860
You start the game,
you watch the movie,

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:10.190
you hit some buttons,
you watch the next movie,

00:04:10.190 --> 00:04:11.260
you hit some buttons.

00:04:11.260 --> 00:04:13.650
Some people like that,
that's one way to play games.

00:04:13.650 --> 00:04:16.603
That's one kind of
game that is out there.

00:04:16.603 --> 00:04:18.269
Not exactly the kind
of games that we're

00:04:18.269 --> 00:04:19.950
making in this class.

00:04:19.950 --> 00:04:23.160
But also not exactly the kind
of games-- not the only way

00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:27.060
to tell stories in games,
as you just mentioned.

00:04:27.060 --> 00:04:30.610
To make those kind of games,
we're calling them AAA games

00:04:30.610 --> 00:04:32.550
if anybody's heard
that phrase before.

00:04:32.550 --> 00:04:35.300
AAA just meaning expensive.

00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:37.520
Blockbuster.

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:39.620
The Marvel blockbuster
movies are basically

00:04:39.620 --> 00:04:42.400
what's happened to
film, Call of Duty

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:44.610
is the game version of that.

00:04:44.610 --> 00:04:46.720
So they require many
expensive resources,

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:47.980
artists, sound designers.

00:04:47.980 --> 00:04:51.200
We heard an artist
talk earlier this week

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:55.070
about how art's important
and why art is important,

00:04:55.070 --> 00:04:56.750
and how difficult
it is for one person

00:04:56.750 --> 00:04:59.780
to do all those different kinds
of tasks that are required

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:03.060
for a complicated game.

00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:05.070
Just to note that
those two games

00:05:05.070 --> 00:05:07.530
that I mentioned
previously usually

00:05:07.530 --> 00:05:08.880
borrow techniques from cinema.

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:12.270
So things like camera placement,
lighting, visual effects

00:05:12.270 --> 00:05:14.060
and sound effects, a
lot of those things

00:05:14.060 --> 00:05:16.750
are their borrowing
concepts from cinema

00:05:16.750 --> 00:05:18.500
that have been proven
to work in cinema,

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:20.125
and then just throwing
them in the game

00:05:20.125 --> 00:05:22.750
because they know they work.

00:05:22.750 --> 00:05:29.016
One way a AAA studio might think
about making a game with story

00:05:29.016 --> 00:05:31.390
is, all right, so it's this
balance between interactivity

00:05:31.390 --> 00:05:33.230
and narrative, right?

00:05:33.230 --> 00:05:37.345
And there's this cost, so think
of that triangle as the cost.

00:05:37.345 --> 00:05:39.310
It costs money to
make these games,

00:05:39.310 --> 00:05:41.930
and that money is generally
either spent on people

00:05:41.930 --> 00:05:46.342
or it's spent on time, so
people times time, basically.

00:05:46.342 --> 00:05:48.050
And the idea is that,
all right, so we've

00:05:48.050 --> 00:05:50.220
got this interactive
stuff going on right here,

00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:51.922
the player presses
buttons, great.

00:05:51.922 --> 00:05:53.380
We've got this
narrative stuff here

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:56.600
and I'm borrowing
comedy and tragedy.

00:05:56.600 --> 00:05:59.810
When I say narrative, think
back to your Aristotle.

00:05:59.810 --> 00:06:02.700
So plot, comedy,
tragedy, melodrama.

00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:05.780
A lot of the AAA games
tend to just basically be

00:06:05.780 --> 00:06:07.356
big melodrama pieces.

00:06:07.356 --> 00:06:08.480
But it could be folk tales.

00:06:08.480 --> 00:06:10.890
That narrative could be--
sometimes it has conflict,

00:06:10.890 --> 00:06:12.181
sometimes there's not conflict.

00:06:12.181 --> 00:06:15.677
Sometimes there's a
dramatic arc or not.

00:06:15.677 --> 00:06:18.010
So they say, all right, so
we've got to balance the two.

00:06:18.010 --> 00:06:19.950
And how do we do that?

00:06:19.950 --> 00:06:23.690
State of the art AAA 2011, this
is Arkham City, that's Batman,

00:06:23.690 --> 00:06:24.960
his parents are dead.

00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:28.920
Press X to pay your respects.

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:31.430
You press the X button,
he places down the rose,

00:06:31.430 --> 00:06:34.047
you get a nice little
cutscene reward with it

00:06:34.047 --> 00:06:35.630
so you can see a
little bit of a movie

00:06:35.630 --> 00:06:40.017
going on with him being grim
and putting down the rose.

00:06:40.017 --> 00:06:42.350
But you also get a little
achievement, so it's a reward,

00:06:42.350 --> 00:06:44.292
it's an Easter egg.

00:06:44.292 --> 00:06:46.250
But it's a crucial back
story to the character,

00:06:46.250 --> 00:06:48.080
they put it in the game.

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:50.660
They spend a lot of money
making that animation.

00:06:50.660 --> 00:06:53.201
Not all players are going to
see it, and when they do see it,

00:06:53.201 --> 00:06:55.190
it only lasts for a very
short period of time.

00:06:55.190 --> 00:06:56.270
That was 2011.

00:06:56.270 --> 00:06:59.190
It's 2014, we've got
really cool computers,

00:06:59.190 --> 00:07:00.990
we've got Xbox One, PS4.

00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:04.960
Your state of the art, AAA, 2014
Call of Duty: Advanced Warfare.

00:07:04.960 --> 00:07:06.300
We've got an upgrade.

00:07:06.300 --> 00:07:09.652
Hold X to pay respects.

00:07:09.652 --> 00:07:11.110
Basically, it's a
quick time event.

00:07:11.110 --> 00:07:13.160
We've seen quick time
events with other games

00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:17.260
before, if anybody's played
Heavy Rain, if anybody's

00:07:17.260 --> 00:07:21.120
played the Shenmue games,
Resident Evil games,

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:22.100
things like that.

00:07:22.100 --> 00:07:24.690
Basically, you've got a
video footage going on,

00:07:24.690 --> 00:07:26.620
and you can press a
button and it'll give you

00:07:26.620 --> 00:07:29.690
a new set of video footage.

00:07:29.690 --> 00:07:31.190
There's a lot of
animation going on,

00:07:31.190 --> 00:07:34.070
there's a lot of
cost going into this.

00:07:34.070 --> 00:07:36.320
I think the hope for
this kind of thing,

00:07:36.320 --> 00:07:39.880
why it's hold X instead of
press X, is by holding X,

00:07:39.880 --> 00:07:43.170
you're embodying that action.

00:07:43.170 --> 00:07:44.920
Maybe you're grieving,
maybe it's praying,

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:46.670
maybe it's holding the button.

00:07:46.670 --> 00:07:49.180
Maybe the longer you hold
it, the more you grieve.

00:07:49.180 --> 00:07:51.680
So maybe there should have been
a score that's counting down

00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:53.590
how much grief you got.

00:07:53.590 --> 00:07:55.770
But if you've read the
internet about the game,

00:07:55.770 --> 00:07:57.634
you notice that,
yeah, it hasn't quite

00:07:57.634 --> 00:08:00.050
worked out the way that they
might have thought it worked.

