00:12:20.920 --> 00:12:22.950
So that's story.

00:12:22.950 --> 00:12:26.950
That's reason is the story
that historians of a game play

00:12:26.950 --> 00:12:30.450
purpose I would argue
that Pac-Man has a story.

00:12:33.150 --> 00:12:34.310
A noticeable story, right?

00:12:34.310 --> 00:12:36.070
There's cutscenes
in this Pac-Man.

00:12:36.070 --> 00:12:39.200
But what's the story of Pac-Man?

00:12:39.200 --> 00:12:42.307
Where are the hints
of story there?

00:12:42.307 --> 00:12:46.059
AUDIENCE: I guess it could be
in how the enemies have names?

00:12:46.059 --> 00:12:47.070
PROFESSOR: Absolutely.

00:12:47.070 --> 00:12:49.125
And why did they give
the characters names?

00:12:51.950 --> 00:12:54.735
Why is Blinky Blinky, and his
character, his personality

00:12:54.735 --> 00:12:55.460
is shadow?

00:12:55.460 --> 00:12:57.424
AUDIENCE: I think as
far as I remember,

00:12:57.424 --> 00:13:00.070
that's really-- the English
translation is a really

00:13:00.070 --> 00:13:02.332
poor translation of it.

00:13:02.332 --> 00:13:05.343
In the original, it's very
clear as to their names

00:13:05.343 --> 00:13:06.884
gives a hint as to
how they will act.

00:13:06.884 --> 00:13:08.090
PROFESSOR: Absolutely.

00:13:08.090 --> 00:13:09.880
They have deterministic actions.

00:13:09.880 --> 00:13:13.010
So I've given them a
little bit of character,

00:13:13.010 --> 00:13:15.810
but that's going to help you to
identify one before the other.

00:13:15.810 --> 00:13:18.290
If anybody's played the Atari
2600 version of Pac-Man,

00:13:18.290 --> 00:13:22.660
my first experience with it, all
the ghosts had the same image.

00:13:22.660 --> 00:13:25.400
You couldn't tell which one
had which type of action.

00:13:25.400 --> 00:13:27.990
They probably actually
didn't have different AI.

00:13:27.990 --> 00:13:29.990
It was a really difficult
game for them to make.

00:13:29.990 --> 00:13:32.310
They had to make it in two
