00:18:03.752 --> 00:18:05.710
So I was asking you about
games telling stories

00:18:05.710 --> 00:18:07.504
and how do games tell stories.

00:18:07.504 --> 00:18:09.670
What I'm going to say now
is that technically, games

00:18:09.670 --> 00:18:12.260
don't exactly tell stories,
if you think about it.

00:18:12.260 --> 00:18:14.280
Like, who is the
storyteller in a game?

00:18:18.650 --> 00:18:19.980
You.

00:18:19.980 --> 00:18:22.120
So it's not storytelling,
it's story building.

00:18:22.120 --> 00:18:24.420
The game, the
designer, the developer

00:18:24.420 --> 00:18:29.000
is giving you the tools to
build a story of your own.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:32.460
Why we say they're different,
so just to compare and contrast,

00:18:32.460 --> 00:18:34.070
storytelling is continuous.

00:18:34.070 --> 00:18:37.820
There's a one way communication,
it is from auteur and author

00:18:37.820 --> 00:18:39.590
to the player.

00:18:39.590 --> 00:18:42.030
The order and, more in
particular, the order of events

00:18:42.030 --> 00:18:44.570
and disclosure of
information is determined

00:18:44.570 --> 00:18:45.870
by the author of the game.

00:18:45.870 --> 00:18:48.328
I'm going to show you this,
and I'm going to show you this,

00:18:48.328 --> 00:18:49.630
and I'm going to show you that.

00:18:49.630 --> 00:18:51.980
Story building is
more fragmented.

00:18:51.980 --> 00:18:54.381
It could be as simple as
I'm going to show you this,

00:18:54.381 --> 00:18:56.130
now you can go see all
these other things,

00:18:56.130 --> 00:18:57.404
but I'm going to
pull you back and I'm

00:18:57.404 --> 00:18:58.550
going to show you
this next thing,

00:18:58.550 --> 00:19:00.620
and you have to see those
two things in order.

00:19:00.620 --> 00:19:02.100
In a more open
oriented game, you

00:19:02.100 --> 00:19:04.500
can see everything
at any point of time

00:19:04.500 --> 00:19:07.000
depending on when you like it.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:08.500
Rather than a one
way communication,

00:19:08.500 --> 00:19:10.416
there's collaboration
between narrative design

00:19:10.416 --> 00:19:11.310
and the players.

00:19:11.310 --> 00:19:15.300
Anybody heard the term
narrative design before?

00:19:15.300 --> 00:19:19.010
Or the job title
narrative designer?

00:19:19.010 --> 00:19:20.702
What do you think
that is in a company?

00:19:20.702 --> 00:19:21.660
And let's say Rational.

00:19:21.660 --> 00:19:23.650
Rational has
narrative designers,

00:19:23.650 --> 00:19:27.200
she was actually a CMS
student for Infinite.

00:19:27.200 --> 00:19:31.915
What would a narrative designer
do in Bioshock Infinite?

00:19:31.915 --> 00:19:35.715
AUDIENCE: Probably write all
the [INAUDIBLE] and stuff,

00:19:35.715 --> 00:19:37.341
and all the little
pops that you hear?

00:19:37.341 --> 00:19:38.174
And what's going on?

00:19:38.174 --> 00:19:39.910
PROFESSOR: A little bit.

00:19:39.910 --> 00:19:42.967
I think Ken wrote a lot of
that, Ken the director wrote

00:19:42.967 --> 00:19:43.550
a lot of that.

00:19:43.550 --> 00:19:45.445
They touch that, though.

00:19:45.445 --> 00:19:46.236
Yeah?

00:19:46.236 --> 00:19:49.163
AUDIENCE: Think of how the story
motivates the player and ties

00:19:49.163 --> 00:19:50.204
into the actual gameplay.

00:19:50.204 --> 00:19:53.676
So like, Bioshock, you're
told to do this and the reason

00:19:53.676 --> 00:19:55.164
is the story.

00:19:55.164 --> 00:19:57.283
I guess figuring
out how that fits in

00:19:57.283 --> 00:19:58.866
and how the mechanics
will be fit into

00:19:58.866 --> 00:20:01.060
PROFESSOR: Yep, they
touch that, too.

00:20:01.060 --> 00:20:03.980
The other thing they do is,
you've got a level designer,

00:20:03.980 --> 00:20:04.980
and you've got a writer.

00:20:04.980 --> 00:20:07.313
And right in between, you've
got the narrative designer.

00:20:07.313 --> 00:20:09.630
In some companies, this
isn't for all companies.

00:20:09.630 --> 00:20:11.575
This is just for some.

00:20:11.575 --> 00:20:13.200
In particular, this
is how I understand

00:20:13.200 --> 00:20:15.985
how Rational works, right,
is the level designer creates

00:20:15.985 --> 00:20:18.270
a level based on how a
person's going to play it,

00:20:18.270 --> 00:20:19.770
how they're going
to get through it,

00:20:19.770 --> 00:20:21.690
how they're going to get
from point A to point B.

00:20:21.690 --> 00:20:23.960
Writer says, here's the story
I need everybody to see,

00:20:23.960 --> 00:20:25.810
here's all the elements
I need them to see.

00:20:25.810 --> 00:20:28.018
Narrative designer figures
out where within the level

00:20:28.018 --> 00:20:29.550
those things are going to exist.

00:20:29.550 --> 00:20:31.383
And we'll talk about
that when we're talking

00:20:31.383 --> 00:20:33.379
about environmental design.

00:20:33.379 --> 00:20:35.920
I'll point out a couple places
where a narrative designer had

00:20:35.920 --> 00:20:37.320
an active role in that game.

00:20:39.887 --> 00:20:41.470
All right, so I'm
going to say that we

00:20:41.470 --> 00:20:43.960
don't need expensive cut
scenes to tell stories.

00:20:43.960 --> 00:20:46.180
We've come up with
a few, we've kind of

00:20:46.180 --> 00:20:47.950
touched on this a little bit.

00:20:47.950 --> 00:20:49.780
And instead, what
I want to say is,

00:20:49.780 --> 00:20:51.490
let's reduce the
cost of the game,

00:20:51.490 --> 00:20:54.040
but let's keep
interactivity and narrative.

00:20:54.040 --> 00:20:56.690
So things a player
does and the story

00:20:56.690 --> 00:20:59.690
that the player experiences
are about similar.

00:20:59.690 --> 00:21:01.790
So what tools are we
going to give the player

00:21:01.790 --> 00:21:03.730
to build their story?

00:21:03.730 --> 00:21:06.380
And where we give them the tools
depends on the type of story

00:21:06.380 --> 00:21:07.590
we're giving them.

00:21:07.590 --> 00:21:12.360
So there's two stories to
games that the player builds.

00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:14.230
There's the story
of the world, which

00:21:14.230 --> 00:21:17.630
largely is seen and heard, and
it's interpreted by the player.

00:21:17.630 --> 00:21:19.740
And there's the story of
the player, the actions

00:21:19.740 --> 00:21:21.850
that the player does,
and why I say told,

00:21:21.850 --> 00:21:23.880
I kind of mean built as well.

00:21:23.880 --> 00:21:25.990
Told is in that the
player is telling it,

00:21:25.990 --> 00:21:27.730
not the-- so the world
might be something

00:21:27.730 --> 00:21:30.074
that the game is
telling the player,

00:21:30.074 --> 00:21:31.740
but the story of the
player is something

00:21:31.740 --> 00:21:33.660
that the player is
telling back to the game,

