00:42:20.500 --> 00:42:22.610
you can burn the
savannah, it's great.

00:42:22.610 --> 00:42:27.470
And you can use that to get
past machine gun emplacement,

00:42:27.470 --> 00:42:29.610
or set a trap for somebody.

00:42:29.610 --> 00:42:34.080
In game character, not
another PC, but in game.

00:42:34.080 --> 00:42:38.560
In an early version of
this, an early test,

00:42:38.560 --> 00:42:41.872
playtesters set fire to the
savannah, and then 10, 15,

00:42:41.872 --> 00:42:44.645
20 minutes later it said
OK, you won the game.

00:42:44.645 --> 00:42:47.310
What happened?

00:42:47.310 --> 00:42:49.080
Fire spread.

00:42:49.080 --> 00:42:53.300
The boss was set in
the fire, in dry grass.

00:42:53.300 --> 00:42:55.900
The fire spread all the
way through the game,

00:42:55.900 --> 00:42:58.320
the many, many miles,
square miles of gameplay,

00:42:58.320 --> 00:43:00.874
and it killed the boss
and ended the game.

00:43:00.874 --> 00:43:03.290
I really wish they had kept
that in, or a version of that.

00:43:03.290 --> 00:43:06.750
They ended up reducing the
spread of fire because of that,

00:43:06.750 --> 00:43:08.270
they moved the
character from it.

00:43:08.270 --> 00:43:10.730
But that's a game event they
could have capitalized on.

00:43:10.730 --> 00:43:12.740
That's a piece of
emergent storytelling

00:43:12.740 --> 00:43:16.170
that's going on that people
tell the story to each other.

00:43:16.170 --> 00:43:19.220
In the developer circles
I heard about this in GDC

00:43:19.220 --> 00:43:21.170
the year after this came out.

00:43:21.170 --> 00:43:22.810
That's a great one.

00:43:22.810 --> 00:43:24.360
So that's game events.

00:43:24.360 --> 00:43:26.160
Next up micronarratives.

00:43:26.160 --> 00:43:27.970
These are similar,
but different.

00:43:27.970 --> 00:43:30.670
A micronarrative is
basically a little bit

00:43:30.670 --> 00:43:34.870
of storytelling inside of
the game that, again, really,

00:43:34.870 --> 00:43:35.520
really small.

00:43:35.520 --> 00:43:36.645
So maybe it's an animation.

00:43:36.645 --> 00:43:38.430
In this case, this
is Jet Set Willy.

00:43:38.430 --> 00:43:41.040
In Jet Set Willy,
you are a rich guy.

00:43:41.040 --> 00:43:44.470
You made all your money in
the previous game by mining,

00:43:44.470 --> 00:43:47.740
and you came home, and you've
invited a bunch of friends

00:43:47.740 --> 00:43:50.060
to your house and you had
this awesome raucous party.

00:43:50.060 --> 00:43:51.630
And you trashed the place.

00:43:51.630 --> 00:43:52.702
Unfortunately, you rent.

00:43:52.702 --> 00:43:54.660
You rent a mansion instead
of buying a mansion.

00:43:54.660 --> 00:43:56.701
And you're trying to go
to bed, and your landlady

00:43:56.701 --> 00:43:59.060
is just like no, you
don't get to go to bed,

00:43:59.060 --> 00:44:00.687
you don't get to sleep.

00:44:00.687 --> 00:44:02.270
You've got to clean
all this stuff up.

00:44:02.270 --> 00:44:03.820
She doesn't say any
of that, though.

00:44:03.820 --> 00:44:06.730
This is all she does.

00:44:06.730 --> 00:44:10.430
Just, she's standing in front
of the bed, she's going that.

00:44:10.430 --> 00:44:13.420
This is for the ZX Spectrum.

00:44:13.420 --> 00:44:18.375
I think it had
64k of RAM, maybe.

00:44:18.375 --> 00:44:19.250
You can look that up.

00:44:19.250 --> 00:44:21.350
Maybe it's 8k,
it's really small.

00:44:21.350 --> 00:44:25.174
Really bad keys,
really bad keyboard.

00:44:25.174 --> 00:44:26.090
Not a lot of graphics.

00:44:26.090 --> 00:44:27.950
That version is actually
a later version,

00:44:27.950 --> 00:44:31.450
I couldn't find-- this is the
closest thing we found for what

00:44:31.450 --> 00:44:32.930
it originally looked like.

00:44:32.930 --> 00:44:35.055
You can really see, there's
character design there,

00:44:35.055 --> 00:44:39.047
but it's also just saying
no, you can't come back here.

00:44:39.047 --> 00:44:46.042
AUDIENCE: 16k at launch,
it did go up to 128.

00:44:46.042 --> 00:44:48.470
PROFESSOR: Now that I've
spewed all this out,

00:44:48.470 --> 00:44:49.824
what can you do with all this?

00:44:49.824 --> 00:44:52.240
So I'm actually going to show
an example of a game created

00:44:52.240 --> 00:44:58.020
last semester by a team in this
class for the final project.

00:44:58.020 --> 00:45:00.480
They made a game
called Sugar Rush.

00:45:00.480 --> 00:45:01.870
What's the game about?

00:45:01.870 --> 00:45:02.870
First, what's the title?

00:45:02.870 --> 00:45:04.040
Well, I told the title.

00:45:04.040 --> 00:45:04.540
Sugar Rush.

00:45:04.540 --> 00:45:06.380
What's the game about?

00:45:06.380 --> 00:45:07.360
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:11.770 --> 00:45:14.500
PROFESSOR: Yeah, candy,
candy, candy, candy, candy.

00:45:14.500 --> 00:45:16.510
Look at him and all that candy.

00:45:16.510 --> 00:45:17.890
And it's a kid.

00:45:17.890 --> 00:45:20.660
So title, character
design, all working really

00:45:20.660 --> 00:45:22.590
well right there.

00:45:22.590 --> 00:45:24.790
Here's the game premise.

00:45:24.790 --> 00:45:26.870
One day, strange
leafy beasts spawn

00:45:26.870 --> 00:45:28.880
from four mysterious
portals, and they

00:45:28.880 --> 00:45:31.980
plundered the villages,
terrorizing Candyland.

00:45:31.980 --> 00:45:34.610
What do you think you're
going to have to do?

00:45:34.610 --> 00:45:37.020
Kill the vegetables.

00:45:37.020 --> 00:45:39.400
And they're mean,
because look at them.

00:45:39.400 --> 00:45:41.390
So mean.

00:45:41.390 --> 00:45:43.630
Now, when we say,
we said don't use

00:45:43.630 --> 00:45:47.110
cutscenes, that doesn't mean
we say don't use exposition.

00:45:47.110 --> 00:45:49.590
A simple screen with a
little bit instructions.

00:45:49.590 --> 00:45:52.830
Basically, we told them,
have an instruction screen.

00:45:52.830 --> 00:45:54.580
This was part of their
instruction screen.

00:45:54.580 --> 00:45:56.621
They had the screen that
says these are the keys,

00:45:56.621 --> 00:45:58.490
but also, this is what you do.

00:45:58.490 --> 00:45:59.950
Really, really useful.

00:45:59.950 --> 00:46:03.160
We want something that fulfills
that for a game the way

00:46:03.160 --> 00:46:04.644
it's necessary for your game.

00:46:04.644 --> 00:46:07.060
The difference between a game
that has something like this

00:46:07.060 --> 00:46:08.601
and doesn't have
something like this,

00:46:08.601 --> 00:46:10.214
is basically it's
a level of polish.

00:46:10.214 --> 00:46:12.380
A game that has a little
bit of exposition like this

00:46:12.380 --> 00:46:15.490
feels a little
bit more concrete.

00:46:15.490 --> 00:46:17.880
It just feels like
it's more complete,

00:46:17.880 --> 00:46:19.470
there's more
thought put into it.

00:46:19.470 --> 00:46:21.680
It just feels a
little bit richer.

00:46:21.680 --> 00:46:24.310
It's still playable without it,
it doesn't need this screen,

00:46:24.310 --> 00:46:27.590
but this screen's
really, really helpful.

00:46:27.590 --> 00:46:29.720
And the game play itself.

00:46:29.720 --> 00:46:33.170
It has mechanics that are
consistent with the design.

00:46:33.170 --> 00:46:35.810
You are a kid, you
are fighting a tomato.

00:46:35.810 --> 00:46:37.630
What do you fight with?

00:46:37.630 --> 00:46:40.640
You have weapons, what are
your weapons made out of?

00:46:40.640 --> 00:46:41.940
Candy.

00:46:41.940 --> 00:46:43.990
How do you heal yourself?

00:46:43.990 --> 00:46:45.320
You eat candy.

00:46:45.320 --> 00:46:46.750
How do you make new weapons?

00:46:46.750 --> 00:46:49.160
You combine and craft candy.

00:46:49.160 --> 00:46:51.630
Everything's revolving
around that premise of candy

00:46:51.630 --> 00:46:53.140
is the world.

00:46:53.140 --> 00:46:57.010
You are the lone human being
in this world that we see.

00:46:57.010 --> 00:46:59.660
And so it's not
like Adventure Time,

00:46:59.660 --> 00:47:02.660
you're not harvesting
candy from candy people.

00:47:05.139 --> 00:47:06.680
The weird thing
about it, I think you

00:47:06.680 --> 00:47:09.490
when you kill vegetables,
you take the candy from them.

00:47:09.490 --> 00:47:11.472
Maybe they're
stealing your candy?

00:47:11.472 --> 00:47:13.680
Yeah, you are stealing the
candy, it says plundering.

00:47:13.680 --> 00:47:17.100
A ha, they thought ahead.

00:47:17.100 --> 00:47:18.316
And yeah, the health points.

00:47:18.316 --> 00:47:20.566
What are the health points
called, if you can read it?

00:47:20.566 --> 00:47:21.585
AUDIENCE: Blood sugar.

00:47:21.585 --> 00:47:22.607
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:47:22.607 --> 00:47:23.440
Really simple stuff.

00:47:23.440 --> 00:47:24.356
Really, really simple.

00:47:24.356 --> 00:47:26.500
Just theming it,
thinking about what

00:47:26.500 --> 00:47:29.760
you call things, how you call
things, where you place things,

00:47:29.760 --> 00:47:31.360
what verbs you're using.

00:47:31.360 --> 00:47:33.660
All that ties into the game.

00:47:37.935 --> 00:47:39.310
Here's another
student made game,

00:47:39.310 --> 00:47:41.010
it was actually made
by a larger team

00:47:41.010 --> 00:47:42.260
over the course of the summer.

00:47:42.260 --> 00:47:44.660
So they actually had nine
weeks to make the game.

00:47:44.660 --> 00:47:47.730
And they had dedicated
artists on this game.

00:47:47.730 --> 00:47:49.550
But this is a game
called Gumbeat which

00:47:49.550 --> 00:47:51.570
we have our website there.

00:47:51.570 --> 00:47:55.260
You are a little girl going
around chewing bubblegum

00:47:55.260 --> 00:47:58.771
in this idyllic land
that, I don't think,

00:47:58.771 --> 00:48:00.270
there's an information
sign up there

00:48:00.270 --> 00:48:01.840
that says keep the place clean.

00:48:01.840 --> 00:48:03.110
Basically, gum's not allowed.

00:48:03.110 --> 00:48:05.670
It's not clean.

00:48:05.670 --> 00:48:07.280
But you go around,
you recruit people.

00:48:07.280 --> 00:48:10.040
You blow bubble gum in front of
them, they say pop the bubble,

00:48:10.040 --> 00:48:12.640
you pop it, they're like
sweet, I'm joining you.

00:48:12.640 --> 00:48:15.152
And then they trail behind you.

00:48:15.152 --> 00:48:17.110
And you see on the right
there, a little guard.

00:48:17.110 --> 00:48:19.990
Metal Gear Solid style, he's
got his own line of sight,

00:48:19.990 --> 00:48:23.170
if he sees you, he's going to
chase you down and hit you.

00:48:23.170 --> 00:48:27.020
Early in the
development, someone--

00:48:27.020 --> 00:48:33.160
so if you pop the bubble on
somebody, like on your friend,

00:48:33.160 --> 00:48:34.330
they'll get stuck with gum.

00:48:34.330 --> 00:48:37.300
You pop the bubble on the guard,
they'll get stuck with gum

00:48:37.300 --> 00:48:39.020
and they'll not be able to move.

00:48:39.020 --> 00:48:42.050
But we found if you put the
bubble gum on the guard,

00:48:42.050 --> 00:48:45.570
and you have a guard, basically
a second guard looking

00:48:45.570 --> 00:48:51.530
for people, all the AI
was was if gum, attack.

00:48:51.530 --> 00:48:56.034
Guard with gum found
the guard, attacked.

00:48:56.034 --> 00:48:57.450
They didn't even
think about this,

00:48:57.450 --> 00:48:59.908
this wasn't a feature they were
planning, it just happened.

00:48:59.908 --> 00:49:02.400
And it happened in the space
of gameplay, play testing,

00:49:02.400 --> 00:49:05.250
just like that
fire in Far Cry 2.

00:49:05.250 --> 00:49:07.250
Except in this case,
they're like, that's really

00:49:07.250 --> 00:49:08.139
freaking awesome.

00:49:08.139 --> 00:49:09.930
We are going to polish
the crap out of that

00:49:09.930 --> 00:49:13.340
and make that a really
interesting feature

00:49:13.340 --> 00:49:13.887
in the game.

00:49:13.887 --> 00:49:15.970
We're not going to tell
the player how to do that,

00:49:15.970 --> 00:49:17.386
but we are going
to create a level

00:49:17.386 --> 00:49:20.040
design that encourages the
player to experiment with that.

00:49:20.040 --> 00:49:21.998
So that's where you get
that kind of game play.

00:49:21.998 --> 00:49:24.730
So play testing is a way to
discover emergent game events.

00:49:24.730 --> 00:49:27.271
So that's why we're asking to
play test your game, especially

00:49:27.271 --> 00:49:29.900
people who are not you, is
to see what-- you've created

00:49:29.900 --> 00:49:31.830
this amazing
possibility space, you

00:49:31.830 --> 00:49:33.850
can't explore the entire
thing on your own.

00:49:33.850 --> 00:49:36.030
They might see something
and not knowing

00:49:36.030 --> 00:49:37.799
what the game is
possible to do and what

00:49:37.799 --> 00:49:39.340
you should be doing
in the game, they

00:49:39.340 --> 00:49:41.990
might come up with some cool
things to do in the game.

00:49:41.990 --> 00:49:45.000
So play testing is key.

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:50.837
Lastly, not a student game, but
another favorite of mine, FTL.

00:49:50.837 --> 00:49:52.920
There is a story to FTL
that's really complicated,

00:49:52.920 --> 00:49:56.460
and I'm not asking you to try
to emulate that sort of thing.

00:49:56.460 --> 00:49:57.372
It's really hard.

00:49:57.372 --> 00:49:59.330
It's a lot of detail and
it's a lot of writing.

00:49:59.330 --> 00:50:02.070
A lot of thought being put into
this randomized event thing.

00:50:02.070 --> 00:50:04.680
But there's a
feature in the game

00:50:04.680 --> 00:50:06.830
that I'm showing here
right now that is only

00:50:06.830 --> 00:50:08.330
used on this screen.

00:50:08.330 --> 00:50:11.960
It's probably kind of-- it was
probably a high price for them

00:50:11.960 --> 00:50:13.590
to put the feature in.

00:50:13.590 --> 00:50:15.257
Can you-- maybe
you can't read it.

00:50:15.257 --> 00:50:16.840
Actually, you can't
read it that well.

00:50:16.840 --> 00:50:19.170
Basically, you can change
the name of the characters.

00:50:19.170 --> 00:50:20.920
This is something that
strategy games have

00:50:20.920 --> 00:50:22.830
had for a long period of time.

00:50:22.830 --> 00:50:28.540
I think we remember through
XCOM back in '93, '94.

00:50:28.540 --> 00:50:29.220
Earlier?

00:50:29.220 --> 00:50:30.740
No, '94.

00:50:30.740 --> 00:50:31.970
So you name your characters.

00:50:31.970 --> 00:50:33.790
If you name your
characters, you might

00:50:33.790 --> 00:50:36.870
be more inclined to make
stories of their game play.

00:50:36.870 --> 00:50:40.680
So I've got my ship as the good
ship GameLab with my buddies

00:50:40.680 --> 00:50:42.980
Andrew, Philip, and
Sarah, and we're

00:50:42.980 --> 00:50:44.729
going to be awesome
and take down--

00:50:44.729 --> 00:50:46.020
are you taking down the empire?

00:50:46.020 --> 00:50:47.090
I can never remember.

00:50:47.090 --> 00:50:47.780
Empire or rebel?

00:50:47.780 --> 00:50:49.020
Are you a rebel or
are you the empire?

00:50:49.020 --> 00:50:50.103
AUDIENCE: You are a rebel.

00:50:50.103 --> 00:50:52.550
PROFESSOR: We're the rebel, OK.

00:50:52.550 --> 00:50:54.392
AUDIENCE: No, actually,
I think you're--

00:50:54.392 --> 00:50:55.850
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
you're the empire.

00:50:55.850 --> 00:50:56.840
You're trying to
take down the rebels.

00:50:56.840 --> 00:50:58.423
AUDIENCE: You have
to run from rebels.

00:50:58.423 --> 00:51:01.120
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:51:01.120 --> 00:51:02.745
OK, cool.

00:51:02.745 --> 00:51:04.870
So one thing that sometimes
happens with this game,

00:51:04.870 --> 00:51:07.290
though, some players are
going to optimize it.

00:51:07.290 --> 00:51:08.790
What did they name
their characters?

00:51:11.880 --> 00:51:14.950
Pilot, Shields, Engines.

00:51:14.950 --> 00:51:15.882
Who's dying?

00:51:15.882 --> 00:51:17.090
Looks like the pilot's dying.

00:51:17.090 --> 00:51:18.380
How do you know?

00:51:18.380 --> 00:51:21.192
It's named Pilot.

00:51:21.192 --> 00:51:22.650
I forget if you
can-- I don't think

00:51:22.650 --> 00:51:25.550
you can rename characters
when you bring them back

00:51:25.550 --> 00:51:26.770
on your ship.

00:51:26.770 --> 00:51:27.770
I should looked that up.

00:51:27.770 --> 00:51:29.910
If anybody plays,
take a look at that.

00:51:29.910 --> 00:51:31.819
But you can get new
characters later on.

00:51:31.819 --> 00:51:34.360
Whether or not you can name them
or not, you might name them,

00:51:34.360 --> 00:51:35.370
you might not name them.

00:51:35.370 --> 00:51:39.090
But either way, they've
spent a lot of time and money

00:51:39.090 --> 00:51:41.690
putting this feature in, some
players aren't going to use it.

00:51:41.690 --> 00:51:43.000
So what do you do?

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:45.480
You blow shit up.

00:51:45.480 --> 00:51:50.210
The game is basically
about traveling the ship,

00:51:50.210 --> 00:51:53.080
things catch on
fire, and hopefully,

00:51:53.080 --> 00:51:54.860
maybe they're not
concerned about Pilot,

00:51:54.860 --> 00:51:56.980
but they are concerned
about their ship.

00:51:56.980 --> 00:51:59.972
So give them these cool little
game events to keep them going.

00:51:59.972 --> 00:52:01.930
GUEST SPEAKER: So one of
the interesting things

00:52:01.930 --> 00:52:04.744
about this kind of story
is that it's actually--

00:52:04.744 --> 00:52:06.160
for all that you're
talking about,

00:52:06.160 --> 00:52:08.120
it does take time and
money to create it,

00:52:08.120 --> 00:52:09.620
but it's actually
pretty cheap to be

00:52:09.620 --> 00:52:11.610
able to let players
name their characters.

00:52:11.610 --> 00:52:13.114
But it's even
cheaper to do it, FTL

00:52:13.114 --> 00:52:15.030
did at the beginning,
where they automatically

00:52:15.030 --> 00:52:16.114
name all their characters.

00:52:16.114 --> 00:52:17.863
When you get a random
human, the character

00:52:17.863 --> 00:52:19.720
isn't named human
number 38, the character

00:52:19.720 --> 00:52:21.721
is named Fred or something.

00:52:21.721 --> 00:52:23.970
And that was actually
originally from the Kickstarter.

00:52:23.970 --> 00:52:26.550
Backers got to have their names
in, which is kind of cool.

00:52:26.550 --> 00:52:28.910
But it's actually worth
doing, because there

00:52:28.910 --> 00:52:30.840
are certain kinds of
players will really

00:52:30.840 --> 00:52:33.120
get into those names in a
way that you don't expect.

00:52:33.120 --> 00:52:36.060
I've got two friends who
really get into their games.

00:52:36.060 --> 00:52:38.992
One, Marc LeBlanc,
was playing XCOM.

00:52:38.992 --> 00:52:41.200
Some of you have seen the
more recent XCOM, I assume?

00:52:41.200 --> 00:52:43.060
But maybe not the old one?

00:52:43.060 --> 00:52:44.910
So you can name your
characters or whatnot.

00:52:44.910 --> 00:52:47.570
And it gives you some
names that you can use.

00:52:47.570 --> 00:52:49.460
He had went through
the entire game,

00:52:49.460 --> 00:52:53.410
and this is back
when games were hard,

00:52:53.410 --> 00:52:56.710
so 40 to 60 hours of
gameplay, and he had

00:52:56.710 --> 00:52:59.030
a squad of super uber soldiers.

00:52:59.030 --> 00:53:00.067
They all had names.

00:53:00.067 --> 00:53:01.900
He didn't quite have
personalities for them,

00:53:01.900 --> 00:53:04.350
but they were kind of
like personalities.

00:53:04.350 --> 00:53:07.630
And the second to final
battle, one of his top A

00:53:07.630 --> 00:53:09.837
squad people got a
broken leg or something.

00:53:09.837 --> 00:53:12.170
And he was like, oh, that's
really annoying, because I'm

00:53:12.170 --> 00:53:13.330
going to Mars tomorrow.

00:53:13.330 --> 00:53:17.220
Well, all my guys that
are high level are gone,

00:53:17.220 --> 00:53:19.430
but I've got these guy's
really cool equipment.

00:53:19.430 --> 00:53:22.810
Like he'd got the laser rifle of
doom and the super uber armor,

00:53:22.810 --> 00:53:24.560
and so he went to his
second string squad,

00:53:24.560 --> 00:53:26.145
the guys who were second level.

00:53:26.145 --> 00:53:29.440
He was like you, suit up,
son, you're going to Mars.

00:53:29.440 --> 00:53:32.320
Which for him was a story, and
it was all inside his head.

00:53:32.320 --> 00:53:33.626
The game didn't make that.

00:53:33.626 --> 00:53:35.000
The game did not
make that story.

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:37.880
The designers could not
have anticipated that story.

00:53:37.880 --> 00:53:39.880
But in his head, because
he's the kind of player

00:53:39.880 --> 00:53:42.500
who really tried to personify
his characters a little bit,

00:53:42.500 --> 00:53:44.969
it was actually a really
big thing for him.

00:53:44.969 --> 00:53:46.510
Similarly, another
one of my friends,

00:53:46.510 --> 00:53:49.480
who will probably come in for
a lecture later, Laura Baldwin,

00:53:49.480 --> 00:53:50.910
was playing XCOM as well.

00:53:50.910 --> 00:53:52.550
Basically the same game.

00:53:52.550 --> 00:53:55.949
She, in her head, kept
all the default names.

00:53:55.949 --> 00:53:57.740
The default name is a
randomized first name

00:53:57.740 --> 00:53:59.540
and a randomized last name.

00:53:59.540 --> 00:54:02.130
And in her head, when she
saw the same last name,

00:54:02.130 --> 00:54:04.256
she assumed that meant the
characters were related.

00:54:04.256 --> 00:54:06.130
Now of course this meant
nothing in the game,

00:54:06.130 --> 00:54:07.202
the game didn't care.

00:54:07.202 --> 00:54:08.660
But here are the
two brothers, here

00:54:08.660 --> 00:54:11.050
are the two sisters,
here's the married couple.

00:54:11.050 --> 00:54:14.420
And so apparently in
the final, final battle,

00:54:14.420 --> 00:54:16.447
you're going in to
destroy the big bad thing,

00:54:16.447 --> 00:54:18.530
and the big bad thing does
horrible psychic damage

00:54:18.530 --> 00:54:20.920
to all of your soldiers
on the map every turn.

00:54:20.920 --> 00:54:22.236
And she was losing horribly.

00:54:22.236 --> 00:54:24.610
And the husband and wife team
made it into the final room

00:54:24.610 --> 00:54:28.750
with the big brain alien,
and the wife runs in

00:54:28.750 --> 00:54:32.330
and discovers the final boss.

00:54:32.330 --> 00:54:35.380
And in XCOM, you
had movement points.

00:54:35.380 --> 00:54:39.780
So she went in and revealed the
fog of war, here's the bad guy.

00:54:39.780 --> 00:54:42.746
She has not enough movement
points to run away.

00:54:42.746 --> 00:54:44.620
And the husband, meanwhile,
is at the doorway

00:54:44.620 --> 00:54:47.260
with a rocket launcher.

00:54:47.260 --> 00:54:49.420
And so apparently, Laura,
the way she tells it,

00:54:49.420 --> 00:54:52.620
she spent about 15 minutes
having a conversation

00:54:52.620 --> 00:54:55.097
between these two characters.

00:54:55.097 --> 00:54:57.180
As the husband's like,
I've got a rocket launcher,

00:54:57.180 --> 00:54:58.980
get out of the way, honey.

00:54:58.980 --> 00:55:01.375
And she's like, I don't
have enough movement points,

00:55:01.375 --> 00:55:03.500
fire the rockets.

00:55:03.500 --> 00:55:04.720
I can't.

00:55:04.720 --> 00:55:06.120
I'll kill you.

00:55:06.120 --> 00:55:08.900
I'm going to die
anway, fire the rocket.

00:55:08.900 --> 00:55:10.950
And this goes back and
forth until finally she

00:55:10.950 --> 00:55:14.920
decides all right,
boom, fires the rocket,

00:55:14.920 --> 00:55:18.250
kills the person next to the
big bad guy, and wins the game.

00:55:18.250 --> 00:55:20.570
But again, this
is because you had

00:55:20.570 --> 00:55:23.130
a player who's very
cooperative, something as simple

00:55:23.130 --> 00:55:24.635
as the names actually helped.

00:55:24.635 --> 00:55:27.260
Now, you can't guarantee you're
going to get players like that.

00:55:27.260 --> 00:55:28.756
